Interface IntegerQueue

All Known Implementing Classes:
CircularArray
public interface IntegerQueue

A queue works much like a line of people waiting for the teller window at the bank. The person at the front of the queue is next to be served and to leave the queue. Newly arrived customers are added at the back of the queue. Consider an element x that is added to the queue (enqueued). Any elements that were enqueued before x are considered to be ahead of x. All elements ahead of x will need to be removed (dequeued) before x can be dequeued. This Queue interface assumes the elements in the queue are ints.

Author:
rhodes

Method Detail

enqueue

void enqueue(int x)
Add an integer x to the CircularArray. This is an enqueue operation, so x is added to the back of the queue. Any elements added before x will be returned by calls to dequeue() before x. If the CircularArray is full, this method throws a java.nio.BufferOverflowException

Parameters:
x - the integer to be added to the back of the queue.
Throws:
java.nio.BufferOverflowException

dequeue

int dequeue()
Dequeue an integer from the front of the queue. Of the all the integers currently in the CircularArray, this method will return the integer least recently enqueued, also removing it from the CircularArray. If this CircularArray is empty, a java.util.NoSuchElementException is thrown.

Returns:
the integer at the front of the queue.
Throws:
java.util.NoSuchElementException

getNumElements

int getNumElements()
Return the number of elements currently in the queue.

Returns:
the number of elements.

isEmpty

boolean isEmpty()
Indicate whether this queue is empty.

Returns:
true if the queue is empty, false otherwise.
